<div class="comment-wrapper"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7321934b88ca8da079d7b89926501a9c?s=50"></div><header><strong>Good things are coming soon in Swift 2.2</strong> from <string>David Turnbull</string> &lt;dturnbull at gmail.com&gt;<p>February  2, 2016 at 11:00:00am</p></header><div class="content"><p>On the swift-dev list they announced the 2.2 branch is now under<br>restrictive change control. If you&#39;re been putting off checking it out, I&#39;d<br>suggest the next snapshot is worth a look.<br></p><p>I did some benchmarks on the last snapshot using a Parks-McClellan filter<br>design algorithm. The algorithm is heavy on floating point arithmetic with<br>a little trig while iterating over arrays.<br></p><p>         C:   2.07ms<br> Swift 2.2:   2.10ms<br> Swift 2.1:   2.70ms<br>  Go 1.5.2:   2.93ms<br>Ruby 2.0.0:  85.50ms<br></p><p><br>Math performance is important to my plans for Swift, so this makes me<br>happy. Ruby and Go haven&#39;t improved on this benchmark in two years.<br></p><p>The Parks-McClellan filter design algorithm is hosted here:<br>https://github.com/AE9RB/firpm<br></p><p>Unfortunately, compile times are longer in 2.2. But one day we&#39;ll have it<br>all.<br></p><p>-david  https://github.com/AE9RB/SwiftGL<br>-------------- next part --------------<br>An HTML attachment was scrubbed...<br>URL: &lt;https://lists.swift.org/pipermail/swift-users/attachments/20160202/c02ce9e3/attachment.html&gt;<br></p></div><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/06c1dcc7dce6a93d194b9c013376e3f0?s=50"></div><header><strong>Good things are coming soon in Swift 2.2</strong> from <string>Joe Groff</string> &lt;jgroff at apple.com&gt;<p>February  2, 2016 at 11:00:00am</p></header><div class="content"><p>&gt; On Feb 2, 2016, at 11:10 AM, David Turnbull via swift-users &lt;swift-users at swift.org&gt; wrote:<br>&gt; <br>&gt; On the s